observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE:

1. Require the MT to deposit intact all collections daily or not later than the next banking day to the authorized depository bank to avoid exposing government funds to the risk of possible misuse or misappropriation and to ensure the availability of cash for the efficient and effective delivery of public service to its constituents;

2.	Require the Municipal Accountant and MT to reconcile the Accounting Book balances and Cashbook balances at least on a quarterly basis. Any significant findings be corrected immediately;

3. Direct the Municipal Accountant to:

Prepare and maintain GLs and SLs for all cash accounts and immediately submit to the Audit Team the required subsidiary schedules of GL balances of cash accounts for all funds and SLs per depository bank and per MT (for current and former, if found to have undeposited collections); and

Ensure that monthly Bank Reconciliation Statements are promptly prepared and submitted to the Audit Team, including bank statements and valid bank debit/credit advices for verification purposes. This will help ascertain the correctness of the Cash in Bank account balance in the financial statements, in compliance with Section 3 of COA Circular No. 96-011.

We recommended that management require:

6. The inventory committee to prepare and submit the approved PIP to the Office of the Auditor at least 10 calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory count and perform the count on all PPE items as indicated in the PIP;

7. The Municipal Accountant to:

Update the PPELC regularly and determine cause/s of the unreconciled amount between the GL and PPELC. Identify details/composition of unreconciled balances and make the necessary adjustments; 

Prepare JEV to recognize all completed projects still under the CIP account to the appropriate PPE accounts; and

Prepare a PPE lapsing schedule and make the necessary entries to record the depreciation of the completed projects still recorded under the CIP account from the year of completion up to December 31, 2023.

We recommended that the management:

8.	Strictly enforce liquidation of the outstanding CAs of the Municipal officials and employees who are still in active service by sending demand letters requiring submission of the liquidation documents for the settlement of their accounts; 

9.	If no settlement is received, enforce the provisions of the COA Circular on the liquidation of CAs, particularly the withholding of salaries of the accountable officers who fail to liquidate their CAs within the prescribed period;

10.	Exert earnest effort in locating the officials and employees who have already retired or resigned, and require settlement/refund of the CAs; and

11.	Require the accounting office to

      review the composition of the advances and due from officer and employees accounts to reconcile the balances presented in the FS and in the Receivables Schedules;

      analyze the cause of advances accounts with negative balances and make appropriate entry to close/adjust the accounts that existed due to erroneous entries; and 

      devise an effective monitoring system for the grant and liquidation of CAs to avoid accumulation of outstanding receivables.

We recommended to management the following:
Send demand letters to employees with outstanding cash advances requiring them to settle unliquidated CAs and do the same on a regular basis;
Require the Municipal Accountant to monitor outstanding cash advances of every official and employee and report the status of their liquidations to the Local Chief Executive on a regular basis for appropriate action by the latter;
For unliquidated cash advances of personnel who are still in active service and after receiving the demand letters, still do not settle their obligation nor made an appropriate justification, immediately withhold their salaries or any amount due them until balances have been fully settled;
Make appropriate disclosures in the Notes to FS on the actual status of unliquidated cash advances for confidential fund, particularly those granted prior to the effectivity of COA-DBM JC No. 2015-01; and
Initiate action to recover unsettled CAs of personnel who were already separated from service upon inability by the latter to respond to demand letters.

We recommended the following to management:

12. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

Cause the immediate full liquidation of outstanding fund transfers received from National Government Agencies and strictly adhere to the provisions of Section 6 of COA Circular No. 94-013 dated December 13, 1994 and Section 3.1.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012;

Collate records to ensure that all unspent balances of fund transfers for completed projects irrespective of source agency be returned;

Exert effort in retrieving records and information to identify the details of fund transfers with outstanding balance and return to source agency if applicable. Otherwise, make recommendation to the Local Chief Executive and Sangguniang Bayan to revert such fund to the General Fund to be used for other social services; and

13. Offices in charge to fast track the implementation of the fund transfers since the resources are readily available in order not to deprive the Municipality of the benefits out of the PPA.

1.16 We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the MT to deposit intact all collections daily or not later than the next banking day to the authorized depository bank to avoid exposing government funds to the risk of possible misuse or misappropriation and to ensure the availability of cash for the efficient and effective delivery of public service to its constituents;
Require the Municipal Accountant and MT to reconcile the Accounting Book balances and Cashbook balances at least on a quarterly basis. Any significant findings be corrected immediately;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
