Ensure that monthly Bank Reconciliation Statements are promptly prepared and submitted to the Audit Team, including bank statements and valid bank debit/credit advices for verification purposes. This will help ascertain the correctness of the Cash in Bank account balance in the financial statements, in compliance with Section 3 of COA Circular No. 96-011.

3.18 We recommended that management require:
The inventory committee to prepare and submit the approved PIP to the Office of the Auditor at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory count and perform the count on all PPE items as indicated in the PIP;
The Municipal Accountant to:
Update the PPELC regularly and determine cause/s of the unreconciled amount between the GL and PPELC. Identify details/composition of unreconciled balances and make the necessary adjustments;
Prepare Journal Entry Vouchers (JEV) to recognize all completed projects still under the CIP account to the appropriate PPE accounts; and
Prepare a PPE lapsing schedule and make the necessary entries to record the depreciation of the completed projects still recorded under the CIP account from the year of completion up to December 31, 2023.

4.6 We recommended that the management:
Strictly enforce liquidation of the outstanding CAs of the Municipal officials and employees who are still in active service by sending demand letters requiring submission of the liquidation documents for the settlement of their accounts;
If no settlement is received, enforce the provisions of the COA Circular on the liquidation of CAs, particularly the withholding of salaries of the accountable officers who fail to liquidate their CAs within the prescribed period;
Exert earnest effort in locating the officials and employees who have already retired or resigned, and require settlement/refund of the CAs; and
Require the accounting office to
review the composition of the advances and due from officer and employees accounts to reconcile the balances presented in the FS and in the Receivables Schedules;
analyze the cause of advances accounts with negative balances and make appropriate entry to close/adjust the accounts that existed due to erroneous entries; and
devise an effective monitoring system for the grant and liquidation of CAs to avoid accumulation of outstanding receivables.

5.8 We recommended the following to management:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Cause the immediate full liquidation of outstanding fund transfers received from National Government Agencies and strictly adhere to the provisions of Section 6 of COA Circular No. 94-013 dated December 13, 1994 and Section 3.1.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012;
Collate records to ensure that all unspent balances of fund transfers for completed projects irrespective of source agency be returned;
Exert effort in retrieving records and information to identify the details of fund transfers with outstanding balance and return to source agency if applicable. Otherwise, make recommendation to the Local Chief Executive and Sangguniang Bayan to revert such fund to the General Fund to be used for other social services; and
Offices in charge to fast track the implementation of the fund transfers since the resources are readily available in order not to deprive the Municipality of the benefits out of the PPA.

We recommended that the management:
strictly enforce liquidation of the outstanding CAs of the Municipal officials and employees who are still in active service by sending demand letters requiring submission of the liquidation documents for the settlement of their accounts;
if no settlement is received, enforce the provisions of the COA Circular on the liquidation of CAs, particularly the withholding of salaries of the accountable officers who fail to liquidate their CAs within the prescribed period;
exert earnest effort in locating the officials and employees who have already retired or resigned, and require settlement/refund of the CAs; and
require the accounting office to devise an effective monitoring system for the grant and liquidation of CAs to avoid accumulation of outstanding cash advances.

We recommended that management require:
The inventory committee to prepare and submit the approved PIP to the Office of the Auditor at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory count and perform the count on all PPE items as indicated in the PIP;
The Municipal Accountant to:
Determine cause/s of the unreconciled amount between the GL and PPELC, exert efforts to identify details/composition of unreconciled balances and make the necessary adjustments;
Identify and provide the lacking information on the PPELC and provide a PPE lapsing schedule. Further to make the necessary adjustments to provide residual values on PPE accounts found to be without it; and
Prepare Journal Entry Vouchers (JEV) to recognize all projects, sufficiently supported with Certificate of Acceptance and Completion and other report, under the CIP account to the appropriate PPE account upon completion.

We recommended and management agreed to:
Submit valid justification why the Pakyaw Contracts were awarded to licensed contractors rather than to Pakyaw labor groups that belong to various Barangay Associations contiguous to the project site;
Refrain from using regular or licensed contractors in the implementation of infrastructure contracts “By Administration” in strict accordance to Appendix 1 of the Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184;
Explain the reason for entering into contract for equipment rental in spite of available the equipment needed for project implementation; and
Award Pakyaw Contracts to pakyaw labor groups for the labor component only of the project.

We recommended that management:
Demand for immediate liquidation and settlement of all cash advances, otherwise for failure of an accountable officer to liquidate his outstanding cash advance, it shall constitute cause for the filing of malversation charge under Article 217; failure to render accounts under Article 218 both of the Revised Penal Code or criminal prosecution under Section 128 of P.O. No. 1445;
No additional cash advances be allowed to any official or employees unless the previous cash advance given to him is first settled;
Appropriate administrative proceedings shall likewise be instituted to erring Officials for non-settlement of their unliquidated cash advances as provided for in COA Circular 2012-004 if warranted; and
File for request of write-off as prescribed by COA Circular No. 2016-005 on dormant accounts if necessary.

We recommended to management that:
Collecting Officers must be duly authorized/designated as such and properly bonded. Officers should desist collecting when they are not duly authorized/designated;
Provide in its Revenue Code rates/charges to be the basis of collecting for the use of its equipment/assets;
Immediately issue Official Receipts to acknowledge collections of all monies due to the LGU and collections should be deposited intact as prescribed; and
Appropriate charges be filed against erring Officials if warranted.

We recommend that management:  1.) refrain  from  granting  additional
cash advances  to  Accountable  Officers  with  previous  unliquidated  cash
advances; 2.) stop the practice of granting cash advances  for  payments  of
account of infrastructure projects or other undertaking on a project  basis;
and 3.) strictly adhere to the provisions set forth in COA  Circular  97-002
in granting and utilization of cash advances;
